1. -- { Hello everyone, and welcome to my first Chessable course! I am GM Alan Pichot 2640 FIDE. Among my sporting achievements, I count the U16 World Championship Durban 2014, as well as having won several important tournaments throughout my career, such as the Zicosur Open Chile, 2016, the Pro Am Open Argentina, 2016 and the Floripa Chess Open Brazil, 2023. I have also participated in two World Cups and two Olympiads. In 2024 I won the Rapid Spanish Championship, the Iberoamerican Championship, and individual Bronze at the Budapest World Chess Olympiad.  However, I am professionally dedicated to competing, so I have much more experience as a player than as a coach.  In 2020, during the pandemic, I had my first experiences as a coach, doing various activities in Chess24, such as opening courses and analysis of the best games of some legends Kasparov, Polgar. I received very good feedback, so I thought it was a good idea to create my own course here on Chessable.  I decided on the King's Gambit because it is a very interesting and challenging opening that forces the Black side to know this system very well. Otherwise, it will be very difficult to find the best way on the board due to the complexity of the position and the amount of options and variants available. I am convinced that the King's Gambit is a great option at high levels, especially in blitz and rapid games. In fact, GM Ian Nepomniachtchi is a regular player of this variation and is one of the top five players in the world.  The King's Gambit was one of the most frequent openings in the 19th century and is considered, with its especially aggressive style of play, the paradigm of romantic chess. As a special mention, we can point out that one of the most famous games in history, Anderssen vs. Kieseritzky 1851, started with this opening. If you don't know this game, you need to go find it right now 🙂 !  I have created this course in a way that is useful to apply in practice, looking for easy to learn positions, creating threats and explaining in detail what we are looking for and what our goal is in each position we play. As I mentioned before, I think the King's Gambit is especially strong in blitz or rapid chess where our opponent has little time to make decisions. It is very important to know in depth what we are playing plans, ideas, etc.. Finally, I consider that this course can be very useful for players up to 2200 FIDE rating. } 

[Event "Killing it with the King's Gambit"]
[White "1) King's Gambit Accepted with 3...g5"]
[Black "3.Nf3 g5 4.h4 with 5.Nxg5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

1. e4 e5 
2. f4 { This move introduces the opening known as King's Gambit. The ideal of this variation is the use of the f file, since we can combine attacks on f7, which is Black's weakest point.   This possible attack can be achieved by combining the rook on f1, the bishop on the c4-f7 diagonal and adding a knight via e5 or g5. The problem we can find is that we leave the e1-h4 diagonal weak, which can often hinder the development of our pieces if we have to move the king from e1. } exf4 
3. Nf3 { I recommend this move over 3.Bc4 mainly because we prevent the move 3...Qh4+ , which would prevent us from castling. In addition, if the king is on f1, it would be more difficult for us to use the f-file to attack. } g5 { Although this move seems to weaken Black's kingside, the aim of such a move is to push the pawn to g4, kick our knight away from f3 in order to be able to play ...Qh4+ and create trouble to our king. } 
4. h4 { Ian Nepomniachtchi, one of the best players in the world today, is the main exponent of this move in rapid and blitz games. This move has 2 purposes: the first one is to prevent Black from playing ...Qh4+ in the future, and the second one is to force Black to push the g pawn forward to weaken their pawn structure so that we can take the f4-pawn. } f6 { Black defends the g5-pawn. } 
5. Nxg5 { A clearance sacrifice to open the diagonal for our queen. } fxg5 
6. Qh5+ { Starting a forced sequence, after which we will have a clear advantage. } Ke7 
7. Qxg5+ Ke8 { Otherwise, we would simply take the queen on d8. } 
8. Qh5+ Ke7 
9. Qe5+ Kf7 
10. Bc4+ { 10.Qxh8 was also possible, but this move wins the queen or leads to checkmate! } Kg6 { The alternative is 10...d5 , but it does not change anything, unless Black wants to give up the queen after 11.Bxd5+ Qxd5 . } 
11. h5+ Kh6 
12. Qxf4+ Qg5 
13. Qxf8+ Qg7 
14. d4 { Checkmate! } 

