1. e4 e5 
2. f4 { This move introduces the opening known as King's Gambit. The ideal of this variation is the use of the f file, since we can combine attacks on f7, which is Black's weakest point.   This possible attack can be achieved by combining the rook on f1, the bishop on the c4-f7 diagonal and adding a knight via e5 or g5. The problem we can find is that we leave the e1-h4 diagonal weak, which can often hinder the development of our pieces if we have to move the king from e1. } exf4 
3. Nf3 { I recommend this move over 3.Bc4 mainly because we prevent the move 3...Qh4+ , which would prevent us from castling. In addition, if the king is on f1, it would be more difficult for us to use the f-file to attack. } g5 { Although this move seems to weaken Black's kingside, the aim of such a move is to push the pawn to g4, kick our knight away from f3 in order to be able to play ...Qh4+ and create trouble to our king. } 
4. h4 { Ian Nepomniachtchi, one of the best players in the world today, is the main exponent of this move in rapid and blitz games. This move has 2 purposes: the first one is to prevent Black from playing ...Qh4+ in the future, and the second one is to force Black to push the g pawn forward to weaken their pawn structure so that we can take the f4-pawn. } g4 
5. Ne5 { We can perceive how the continuous advance of Black's pawns is leaving them weaker and weaker. } d6 { Black aims to kick our most threatening piece. } 
6. Nxg4 { The sacrifice 6.Nxf7? does not work due to 6...Kxf7 7.Bc4+ Ke8 8.d4 seizing the center and aiming to take the f4-pawn to open the f-file 8...Bh6 this move highlights the main problem of our position! Black's f4 and g4 pawns are well defended, so Black's king is safe even in the center of the board 9.O-O Qxh4 and Black is threatening ...g3 followed by mate on h2! } Bxg4 { A very natural capture, but Black removes our weird placed knight on g4. } 
7. Qxg4 Bh6 { In practice, Black usually plays 7...Nf6 , which allows us to play the simple 8.Qxf4 getting a clean pawn material advantage, the bishop pair, and the f-file to attack. Black can also play 7...Qf6 to defend the f4-pawn,but after 8.Qc8+ followed by 9.Qxb7 gives White a decisive advantage! And these variations are the most frequently seen in games of up to 2000 ELO players. } 
8. d4 { Seizing the center and threatening the f4-pawn. } Nc6 
9. Bb5 { Developing our light squared bishop and defending d4. } Nf6 
10. Qf5 { Black is facing difficult problems in this position: White threatens d4-d5, winning material, the f4-pawn will fall and Black's king is weak in the center! } 

