1. e4 e5 
2. f4 { This move introduces the opening known as King's Gambit. The ideal of this variation is the use of the f file, since we can combine attacks on f7, which is Black's weakest point.   This possible attack can be achieved by combining the rook on f1, the bishop on the c4-f7 diagonal and adding a knight via e5 or g5. The problem we can find is that we leave the e1-h4 diagonal weak, which can often hinder the development of our pieces if we have to move the king from e1. } exf4 
3. Nf3 { I recommend this move over 3.Bc4 mainly because we prevent the move 3...Qh4+ , which would prevent us from castling. In addition, if the king is on f1, it would be more difficult for us to use the f-file to attack. } g5 { Although this move seems to weaken Black's kingside, the aim of such a move is to push the pawn to g4, kick our knight away from f3 in order to be able to play ...Qh4+ and create trouble to our king. } 
4. h4 { Ian Nepomniachtchi, one of the best players in the world today, is the main exponent of this move in rapid and blitz games. This move has 2 purposes: the first one is to prevent Black from playing ...Qh4+ in the future, and the second one is to force Black to push the g pawn forward to weaken their pawn structure so that we can take the f4-pawn. } g4 
5. Ne5 { We can perceive how the continuous advance of Black's pawns is leaving them weaker and weaker. } d6 { Black aims to kick our most threatening piece. } 
6. Nxg4 { The sacrifice 6.Nxf7? does not work due to 6...Kxf7 7.Bc4+ Ke8 8.d4 seizing the center and aiming to take the f4-pawn to open the f-file 8...Bh6 this move highlights the main problem of our position! Black's f4 and g4 pawns are well defended, so Black's king is safe even in the center of the board 9.O-O Qxh4 and Black is threatening ...g3 followed by mate on h2! } Be7 { This move is the one that worries me a bit more in this line, since it is the one that scores best with Black, but we have good resources to achieve a nice position! } { 6...Nf6 transposes to the 6...d6 main line. } 
7. d4 { Giving up the h4-pawn but building a strong pawn center. } Bxh4+ 
8. Nf2 Bg3 { Black seeks to hold on to the f4 pawn while keeping our position cramped. } 
9. Qf3 Qf6 
10. Nc3 { Following the spirit of the opening, we play dynamically! } { The natural move 10.c3? h5! leads to a decisive advantage for Black, since we cannot avoid the strong 11...Bg4! } Qxd4 
11. Nb5 Qb6 { A natural queen retreat. The idea is to defend c7. } 
12. Bxf4 { We immediately take the pawn and release Black's pressure on the kingside. } Bxf4 
13. Qxf4 Nc6 
14. a4 { This move has some hidden tricks up the sleeve that I will explain in our next move. } a6 
15. a5 { We give up a pawn, but with the intention of combining movess such as Qg3-Qg7 or Qc3 attacking the h8-rook. } Nxa5 
16. Qg3 { Black is defenseless against our multiple threats. } axb5 
17. Qg7 { Once we take the rook, we will be an exchange up, the knight on a5 will be pinned and we will also win the h7 pawn. Another important point is that Black will be left with very uncoordinated pieces! } 

