11. Kd2 { The critical position of this variation. It seems that White's king is in a rather ugly position, but at the same time, if we manage to play c3-Kc2, White's position will change drastically. However, Black has several moves at his disposal, which we will see below. } { Please notice that 11.Ke2?? Bg4+ . } Nd4 { If 11...Nb4 , 11...Ne7 or 11...Bh6 , our plan will be the same. We will play 12.Qf3 to stop our opponent's threats and then we will try to outplay our opponent in this even endgame where our point is to take Black's f4-pawn. } 
12. c3 { 12.Nxc7+?? loses to 12...Kd8 13.Nxa8 Qf2+ 14.Kc3 Bg7 and Black's attack is so strong. } c6 
13. Nf6+ Ke7 
14. cxd4 { 14.Nh5 is not possible due to 14...Qe3 ¡checkmate! } Kxf6 
15. Be2 Qxg2 { If 15...Bh6 16.Kc2 and in this position we should to focus our efforts on taking the f4 pawn and taking advantage of the bad position of the black king. } 
16. Kc3 { Unpining the e2-bishop and threatening the f4-pawn. } Bh6 
17. Bxf4 Bxf4 
18. Rf1 { We will get the piece back and we will be able to exert strong pressure on f7, which makes our position better and simpler to play. } 

