1. e4 e5 
2. f4 { This move introduces the opening known as King's Gambit. The ideal of this variation is the use of the f file, since we can combine attacks on f7, which is Black's weakest point.   This possible attack can be achieved by combining the rook on f1, the bishop on the c4-f7 diagonal and adding a knight via e5 or g5. The problem we can find is that we leave the e1-h4 diagonal weak, which can often hinder the development of our pieces if we have to move the king from e1. } exf4 
3. Nf3 { I recommend this move over 3.Bc4 mainly because we prevent the move 3...Qh4+ , which would prevent us from castling. In addition, if the king is on f1, it would be more difficult for us to use the f-file to attack. } g5 { Although this move seems to weaken Black's kingside, the aim of such a move is to push the pawn to g4, kick our knight away from f3 in order to be able to play ...Qh4+ and create trouble to our king. } 
4. h4 { Ian Nepomniachtchi, one of the best players in the world today, is the main exponent of this move in rapid and blitz games. This move has 2 purposes: the first one is to prevent Black from playing ...Qh4+ in the future, and the second one is to force Black to push the g pawn forward to weaken their pawn structure so that we can take the f4-pawn. } g4 
5. Ne5 { We can perceive how the continuous advance of Black's pawns is leaving them weaker and weaker. } Nf6 { The main move in this position. Black develops their first piece to defend the g4-pawn and to threaten our e4-pawn. } 
6. Nxg4 Nxe4 { This move will lead to quite interesting lines! Now the knight can go to g3, looking to harass our kingside, especially the rook on h1. } 
7. d3 Ng3 { It seems we are in trouble, but... } 
8. Bxf4 Nxh1 { It's natural to grab the rook, but... } 
9. Qe2+ Qe7 { 9...Be7?? 10.Nf6+ Kf8 11.Bh6 . } 
10. Nf6+ Kd8 
11. Bxc7+ { Sacrificing another piece to win the queen. } Kxc7 
12. Nd5+ Kd8 
13. Nxe7 Bxe7 { We arrive at an unclear position where White exchanged 3 pieces for the queen, but the h1-knight has difficulties to return to the game, and the a8 rook will take a long time to enter the game, while White can quickly activate their pieces. } 
14. Qf3 Bxh4+ 
15. Kd2 { Tempting Black to move the bishop away from h4, after which the knight is not able to come back to the game via f2 or g3! } { 15.Kd1?! is dubious because Black can combine a pin with a double attack to get the advantage: 15...d6 16.Qh5 Bg4+!! 17.Qxg4 Nf2+ . } Bg5+ { Only move to avoid losing a piece } { 15...d6 16.Qh5 } 
16. Kd1 { In practice, this position is easier to play as White due to the lack of coordination of Black's forces. } 

