2. f4 exf4 
3. Nf3 g5 
4. h4 g4 
5. Ne5 Qe7 { It is not a very frequent move in this position, but it is important to mention it since it leads to positions that are not so common in the king's gambit. } 
6. d4 d6 { The knight on e5 is very strong, so Black seeks to bring it out immediately. } 
7. Nxg4 Qxe4+ 
8. Qe2 { This variation is one of the few within the King's Gambit where we are forced to exchange queens in the opening, so we are going to analyze a little the ending that is reached. } Qxe2+ 
9. Bxe2 { We are a pawn down, but the f4 pawn is very difficult to hold. } Nc6 
10. c3 h5 { It is the only way to play to hold the f4-pawn, otherwise we will play Bxf4 and reach a comfortable endgame. } 
11. Nf2 Bh6 
12. Nd3 { 12.Bxh5?? very important detail: do not fall into the temptation of the h5 pawn! 12...f3!! 13.Bxh6 fxg2 14.Rg1 Rxh6 our h4-pawn is going to fall, and we have a pretty sad endgame } Bf5 
13. O-O { It is not necessary to take the pawn quickly, we can castle and improve the king. } O-O-O { Playing with the king in the center of the board is not an option, and considering that Black has a weakness in the h5-pawn, castling long seems a quite reasonable option. } 
14. Nxf4 { Now the h5-pawn starts to be a weakness. } Nf6 { 14...Bxf4? 15.Bxf4 this ending is excellent for White with the bishop pair, Black cannot allow it. } 
15. Nd3 Ne7 { It seems that Black is in trouble, but he always arrives on time with Ne7. } 
16. Bxh6 Rxh6 
17. Nd2 { We finally get to this even position, where it is a bit more comfortable to play with White, since we have the f-file to put pressure on, it is important to bring the a1-rook into play quickly. } 

