6. Nc3 Nc6 { There are only few records of games with this sideline, but you have to take it into account. } { 6...Bg4 7.d4 transposes to 5...Bg4. } 
7. d4 Nh5 { Important move. It defends the f4-pawn and keeps an eye on the g3-square. } 
8. Nd5 { We seek to recover the pawn. } Ng3 
9. Rh2 { We need to continue defending the h4-pawn, which is preventing the g5-push. } Be7 { 9...Nxe4 10.Qe2 f5 11.Bxf4 and Black has problem with safety of their uncastled king still on the e8-square. We are threatening 12.Ne5 knight jump to make a free way for our queen to the h5-square with deadly check. } 
10. Bxf4 Nxe4 
11. Qe2 Nf6 { The best move for Black. } { In case of 11...Bf5 we win a piece after 12.Bd3 . 11...f5 prevents Black from losing on the spot, but they will suffer with the king stuck in the center. } 
12. Nxf6+ gxf6 
13. d5 { We prevent Black from solidify their position with simply manoeuvre: the d6-d5 pawn advance followed by the bishop c8-e6 move. We should keep Black's development strictly restricted. } Ne5 
14. O-O-O Bg4 
15. Qf1 { Now our opponent must carefully choose his continuation, since the king will have problems on both flanks. } Nxc4 { A double-edged choice, since the centralized e5-knight was a strong piece. } 
16. Qxc4 Qd7 
17. Rhh1 { And we reach a slighty better position for White, according to Stockfish 16.1 NNUE at 40 depth, in which White's pieces are better placed, while Black's rooks cannot easily enter into play. If Black opt for long castling, we can start an attack by the rook Rd3 lift. If the black king moves to f8-square, we can put our rooks on both e- and f-files to apply more pressure. } 

