1. e4 e5 
2. f4 exf4 
3. Nf3 Be7 { An interesting move, as the idea is to give check on h4 to prevent White's castling. } 
4. Bc4 { In the spirit of this gambit, we develop a piece and accept the option of playing without castling. } Nf6 
5. e5 Ng4 
6. d4 Bh4+ { An apparently strong move, as Black's knight will invade via f2, but we have good weapons to combat this. } 
7. Kf1 Ne3+ { This move makes a lot of sense, at it gives the pawn back in return of removing our dark-squared bishop from the board. } 
8. Bxe3 { Only move. } fxe3 
9. Qd3 { Although the main goal is to attack e3, we can also add plans to attack h7.. } O-O { In case of 9...Bf2 first, we can transpose to the main line with 10.Qe4 . } 
10. Qe4 Bf2 { Defending the pawn, but in exchange for not being able to bring the bishop back to the game. } 
11. Nc3 { A move with two purposes: being able to play Nd1, to get the pawn back by taking twice on f2 and the second, and more important, this move allows the knight to join the attack via e4. } d6 
12. Bd3 { This move already forces Black to weaken the dark squares around their castled king. In addition, the main defender of the dark squares is far away on f2. } g6 
13. Qf4 { Aiming to invade Black's position via h6 and leaving the e4-square for the knight. From now on our opponent must defend in a very concrete way. } dxe5 
14. Qh6 f6 
15. h4 { Aiming for h5 to break Black's king wall. } Qe7 
16. h5 g5 
17. Nd5 { After this move, White wins, at least, the rook on a8. } Qg7 { 17...Qf7 is met by 18.Nxf6+ and White wins easily with moves such as 19.Qxh7 or Nxh7. } 
18. Qxg7+ Kxg7 
19. h6+ Kf7 
20. Nxc7 { White has a clear advantage. } 

