1. e4 e5 
2. f4 d5 
3. exd5 c6 { The trick of this move is that White's natural moves like 4.fxe5 and 4.Nf3 are bad, so you have to know how to play against this move! } 
4. Qe2 { 4.fxe5?? Qh4+! } cxd5 
5. fxe5 Nc6 
6. Nf3 Bg4 { It is important to mention that unlike the most common variations of the King's Gambit where we have a pawn down in exchange for counterplay, in this case it is the other way around! We have an extra pawn, and Black is going to try to look for counterplay in exchange. } 
7. Nc3 d4 { It is important for Black to play actively. } 
8. Ne4 Qd5 { 8...Nxe5?? it is important to know this trick, here we are going to win in a very elegant way 9.Nf2!! Bxf3 10.Qxe5+ . } 
9. Nf2 { Again the same move, the idea is that black can recover the pawn but in exchange we keep the pair of bishops. } Bxf3 
10. gxf3 Qxe5 { There is no other way to play, black has to get the pawn back. } 
11. Qxe5+ Nxe5 
12. f4 { And finally we get this good position, where we have the bishop pair in an open position and easier to play. } 

