23. Qxd1 { White has a decisive advantage. Black's pieces have no activity at all. } 

[Event "Killing it with the King's Gambit"]
[White "10) 2...Nc6 sideline "]
[Black "2...Nc6 3.Nf3 d5 4.exd5 Qxd5 5.Nc3 #8"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

1. e4 e5 
2. f4 Nc6 
3. Nf3 d5 { 3...d6 This move suggests an approach with a more open position for our opponent, but in exchange we will gain some tempi against the queen. } 
4. exd5 Qxd5 
5. Nc3 Qe6 
6. Be2 { We block the file and prepare O-O, taking advantage of the fact that the black queen is on the same file as their king. } exf4 { The most popular in practice, but White will get an excellent position. } 
7. d4 Qf6 { Attacking d4. } 
8. O-O Bg4 
9. Nd5 Qd8 { If 9...Qd6 , defending c7, we have the strong reply 10.c4 and 11.Bxf4 next, with a strong threat to the c7-pawn. } 
10. Bc4 { Defending the d5-knight, opening the e-file to attack and pointing to f7. } Nge7 
11. Nxf4 { After this move, we enter a tactical sequence that leaves us with a clear advantage. } Bxf3 { Logical, to remove the defender of d4. } 
12. Bxf7+ { Black's king is now completely exposed. } Kxf7 
13. Qxf3 Nxd4 { 13...Qxd4+ 14.Be3 Qf6 15.Qe4 Ke8 16.Ne6 and the rook on a8 inevitably falls. } 
14. Qd3 { Keeping the discovered attack on the menu and aiming to add an attacker along the c4-f7 diagonal. } Qd6 
15. Be3 { As the discovered checks are not good enough, we take the opportunity to finish our development and bring those forces to the attack. } Nf3+ { Trying to simplify the position, but our position will be preferrable, as we will see. } 
16. Rxf3 Qxd3 
17. Nxd3+ Kg8 { 17...Ke8 would be met by 18.Re1 and Black has a lot of issues on the e-file, as we are threatening strong moves such as Bc5 or Bg5 targetting e7. } 
18. Raf1 { Black's pieces are badly placed and out of the game, that is why White should play this position energetically. } Re8 
19. Rf7 { White has a decisive advantage, as Black's pieces are completely frozen. One idea could be Bc5 followed by Rxf8, aiming for a clearly favorable endgame of rook vs 2 pieces. } 

[Event "Killing it with the King's Gambit"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Anderssen, Adolf vs. Kieseritzky, Lionel"]
[Result "1-0"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

1. e4 e5 
2. f4 exf4 
3. Bc4 { An interesting, but not so popular, alternative to 3.Nf3 which can be used to catch your opponents by surprise. } b5 { It seems that 3...Nc6 is a more natural move, starting the development. 4.Nf3 g5 . } { 3...Qh4+ 4.Kf1 Nf6 5.Nf3 Qh6 we will reach a similar position in the game, with the difference that Kieseritzky chose to play b5 first; he probably wanted to avoid some trouble on the f7-square. } 
4. Bxb5 Qh4+ 
5. Kf1 Nf6 
6. Nf3 Qh6 
7. d3 { 7.Nc3!? would have been a bit better, since our idea is to try to build a strong pawn center with d4 and e4, and to get there it is essential to have everything defended first. } Nh5 { Simply threatening ...Ng3+, winning the exchange. } 
8. Nh4 { 8.Rg1! was strong, preventing ...Ng3. Now it is White who aims to attack on the kingside with moves such as g4! We should punish the poor placement of the Black's queen and knight. } c6 
9. Nf5 Qg5 
10. g4 { The quiet 10.Ba4!? instead was also possible. } Nf6 { 10...g6! is very difficult to play in a real game. The bishop on b5 is under attack; Black is threatening our knight and our best and simplest reply is to create another threat! Positions that require accurate calculation are not easy to play 11.gxh5 gxf5 12.Rg1 Qh4 and Black gets a comfortable advantage. } 
11. Rg1 cxb5 { 11...h5! was a great move! Now White will not be able to play h4-h5 quickly, harassing Black's queen. 12.h4 Qg6 . } 
12. h4 Qg6 
13. h5 Qg5 
14. Qf3 { We have an amazing position on the board! White is a piece down, but Black's queen has no safe squares to go to, and the Bxf4 threat would be fatal if allowed. } Ng8 
15. Bxf4 Qf6 { This is a clear example of how important piece development is. Black is a piece up, but is lost because of lack of development, and White's dangerous initiative. } 
16. Nc3 Bc5 
17. Nd5 Qxb2 
18. Bd6 { 18.Re1! was also strong, with a decisive advantage for White. } Bxg1 { 18...Qxa1+ 19.Ke2 Qxg1 20.Nxg7+ Kd8 21.Bc7 } 
19. e5 { The Immortal!! White sacrificed the bishop on b5 before, and now they are to give up two rooks for an unstoppable attack against Black's king. } Qxa1+ 
20. Ke2 Na6 { 20...Ba6 would have been more tenacious, although there is not much left to be done at this point. 21.Nc7+ Kd8 22.Nxa6! } 
21. Nxg7+ Kd8 
22. Qf6+ Nxf6 
23. Be7 { An exquisite finish to one of the most famous games in history, which includes the sacrifice of the bishop on b5, then the two rooks and the final touch by sacrificing the queen on f6. All to give mate with only three pieces left. } 

[Event "Killing it with the King's Gambit"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Petrov, Alexander vs. Hoffmann, F.."]
[Result "1-0"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

1. e4 e5 
2. f4 exf4 
3. Bc4 Qh4+ 
4. Kf1 g5 { Better is 4...Nc6 . For some strange reason, XIX century players disliked to develop their pieces quickly! } 
5. Nc3 Bg7 
6. d4 Ne7 
7. e5 { 7.g3! is a move very difficult to find in practice, but it hides a powerful tactical blow: 7...fxg3 8.Kg2!! and Black's queen has no good squares to hide! 8...d6 9.hxg3 Qg4 10.Be2 Qe6 11.Bxg5 We got the pawn back and we have a great advantage in development and space. } Nf5 { 7...O-O ! I repeat the same thing: it is VERY important to always be aware of the basic concepts of piece development and king safety! } 
8. Nf3 Qh5 
9. Kg1 { At the moment it is not clear what is the intention of this move, but we will soon find it out! } h6 { 9...Nc6! Both Hoffmann and Kieseritzky had big problems because they did not develop the knight to c6 properly when they should have done so 10.Nd5 Nfxd4!! } 
10. Nd5 Kd8 
11. h4 { Now the rook on h1 is defended by the king, so we are threatening the strong hxg5, which was not possible before with the king on f1. } Qg6 
12. hxg5 hxg5 
13. Rxh8+ Bxh8 
14. Nxg5 { Great move! Sacrificing the knight in exchange for the very strong bishop development to f4 and more than interesting attack against the black king, due to the lack of development of Black's pieces. } Qxg5 
15. Bxf4 Qg6 
16. e6 { After the sequence 16.Qd2! Nc6 17.Bg5+ Ke8 18.Nxc7+ Kf8 19.Nxa8 Ncxd4 20.Re1 Black is lost, although it must be noted that the position is still complicated, and it is necessary to play accurately in order to be able to materialize this advantage. } Bxd4+ { 16...dxe6! Neither player saw this simple, winning sequence! 17.Bxc7+ 17.Nxc7 Bxd4+ 18.Kf1 e5 and Black has a winning position Kd7 18.Nf4 Bxd4+ 19.Qxd4+ Nxd4 20.Nxg6 Kxc7 White is a piece down in a completely lost endgame. } 
17. Qxd4 Nxd4 
18. exf7 { What an amazing position! We have only one pawn in exchange for the queen and, yet, according to the engine, we have a winning position! All this is thanks to the wonderful coordination of our pieces and Black's lack of development. } Nf3+ 
19. Kf2 Qxf7 { After 19...Qxc2+ 20.Kxf3 Qf5 21.Rh1 , Black's position is resignable as their hopes are over. } 
20. gxf3 Qf5 { Black should try 20...Qxf4 21.Nxf4 , although the material is equal, Black's position is very difficult due to significant lack of development. } { 20...d6 21.Bg5+ Kd7 22.Nf6+ Qxf6 23.Bxf6 even though the material is equal, Black's a quite noticeable lack of development makes their position almost desperate. } 
21. Bxc7+ Ke8 
22. Re1+ Kf8 
23. Bd6+ Kg7 
24. Re7+ Kh6 { 24...Kh8 25.Be5+ Qxe5 26.Rxe5 Nc6 27.Re8+ and White is completely winning thanks to their passed pawn on the f-file and, in addition, Black is on the verge of being in zugzwang. } 
25. Bd3 { A nice final touch! } Qxd5 
26. Bf4+ { As in Anderssen's game, White sacrificed almost all of their pieces in exchange for the strong threats against the black king, and it only took 3 pieces to deliver the final blow. Meanwhile we can see the postcard of the black pieces that none of them managed to get out of their initial square! } 

